# Engineering Security

Universal security principles applied whenever writing or reviewing code that handles input, identity, secrets, or sensitive data.

These principles apply regardless of language, framework, or technology stack.

---

## Validate all input at the boundary

- Never trust caller-supplied data; validate type, format, range, and length before use
- Reject invalid input explicitly; do not attempt to sanitise and proceed
- Validation belongs at the entry point of the system, before any processing

---

## Least privilege

- Code, services, and users should request only the permissions they need
- Default to restrictive; require explicit grant for elevated access
- If a service does not need write access to a database table, it should not have it

---

## Authenticate before authorising

- Always verify identity before checking permissions
- Do not allow partial or anonymous access to sensitive operations unless intentional and documented
- Enforce authentication and authorisation at the boundary; do not rely on callers doing it correctly

---

## Authorise at the resource level

- Check that the authenticated user is permitted to access the specific resource being requested
- Do not rely only on role checks; verify resource ownership in business logic
- Missing authorisation on one endpoint is sufficient for an access control failure

---

## Secrets belong in secrets management

- Never store secrets in source code, configuration files committed to source control, or environment variables set in code
- Inject secrets from a secrets store at runtime (vault, environment, or managed identity)
- Rotate secrets on compromise; prefer short-lived tokens over long-lived credentials

---

## Protect against injection

- Use parameterised queries or ORM methods for all database access; never concatenate user input into SQL
- Validate and escape output in rendering contexts; do not trust stored data as safe to render
- Treat all external input — headers, query parameters, request bodies, file names — as potentially hostile

---

## Secure by default

- New endpoints are authenticated by default; opt-in for public access, not opt-out
- New fields are not logged by default; sensitive data is explicitly excluded
- New services start with minimal permissions; expand only as needed

---

## Never log sensitive data

Do not include in log output:

- Passwords, tokens, API keys, private keys
- Full payment card numbers (PAN), CVV, bank account numbers
- National identity numbers, tax file numbers
- Full names combined with addresses, birthdates, or health data

Mask or exclude these fields at the log sink level, not by developer discipline alone.

---

## Cryptography: use the standard

- Do not implement custom cryptographic algorithms
- Use platform-provided, industry-standard implementations (AES-256, RSA-2048, SHA-256 or higher)
- Never use MD5 or SHA-1 for security purposes
- Use TLS 1.2+ for all network transport; enforce HSTS for web applications

---

## Dependency hygiene

- Keep dependencies updated; outdated packages with known CVEs are a vulnerability
- Check for vulnerable packages regularly (automated scanning in CI/CD)
- Remove unused dependencies

---

## Error responses do not reveal internals

- Return generic error messages to unauthenticated or unauthorised callers
- Do not expose stack traces, database errors, or internal exception details in API responses
- Log detailed errors server-side for diagnostics; return minimal details client-side

---

## OWASP Top 10 quick reference

| Risk | Default mitigation |
|------|------------------|
| A01 Broken access control | Authorise at boundary and resource level |
| A02 Cryptographic failures | Use standard libraries; enforce TLS |
| A03 Injection | Parameterise all queries; validate all inputs |
| A04 Insecure design | Threat model; architecture review |
| A05 Security misconfiguration | Remove defaults; restrict CORS; disable debug in production |
| A06 Vulnerable components | Automated dependency scanning; regular updates |
| A07 Auth and session failures | Short token TTL; validate all JWT claims |
| A08 Software and data integrity | Signed packages; secure CI/CD pipelines |
| A09 Logging and monitoring failures | Structured logs; alert on auth anomalies |
| A10 SSRF | Allowlist outbound URLs; validate scheme and host |

---

## Security review checklist

- [ ] All inputs are validated before use
- [ ] No parameterised query exceptions or raw SQL with user input
- [ ] No secrets in configuration files or code
- [ ] All endpoints require authentication unless explicitly public
- [ ] Resource ownership is verified in handlers
- [ ] No sensitive data in log output
- [ ] Dependencies are current and not flagged as vulnerable
- [ ] Error responses do not reveal internal details
- [ ] TLS is enforced; HSTS is configured for web apps
